MT: Model-based Adjustments for Non-concurrent Comparisons in Platform Trials - preliminary simulations

Pavla Krotka, Marta Bofill Roig

2023-04-12

1 Introduction

The following preliminary simulation study aims to explore different approaches to perform treatment-control comparisons using non-concurrent controls (NCC), where the time trend is modeled using fixed effect models, mixed effect models and splines. In the considered scenarios, continuous endpoints are assumed.

2 Investigated models

Fixed effect models:

  • with period adjustment
  • with calendar time adjustment

Mixed effect models:

  • with period adjustment
  • with calendar time adjustment
  • with period adjustment and AR1 covariance structure
  • with calendar time adjustment and AR1 covariance structure

Spline regression:

  • polynomial splines with knots placed according to periods
  • polynomial splines with knots placed according to calendar times
  • piecewise polynomials (discontinuous) per period
  • piecewise polynomial (discontinuous) per calendar time

3 Time trend patterns

4 Scenario with 4 arms

  • 4 experimental treatment arms
  • \(n=250\)
  • equal time trend - \(\lambda \in [-0.5; 0.5]\)
  • entry times \(d_i = 250 \cdot (i-1)\)
  • \(\theta_k=0.25\) under \(H_1\)
  • linear, stepwise (jump only when new arm enters), inverted u (\(N_{peak}=750\)) and seasonal (\(\psi=1,2\)) time trends
  • inference for 3rd treatment arm

5 Scenario with 7 arms

  • 7 experimental treatment arms
  • \(n=250\)
  • equal time trend - \(\lambda \in [-0.5; 0.5]\)
  • entry times \(d = 250 \cdot (0,1,1,2,2,3,3)\)
  • \(\theta_k=0.25\) under \(H_1\)
  • linear, stepwise (jump only when new arm enters), inverted u (\(N_{peak}=914\)) and seasonal (\(\psi=1,2\)) time trends
  • inference for 7th treatment arm
